article.description:
Rookie Diana Taurasi had 22 points and eight rebounds to lead Phoenix to a 71-69 victory Thursday night over Sacramento, ending the Mercury's eight-game losing streak
against the Monarchs.
article.headline: Taurasi scores 22 in victory
article.linkText: Mercury end 8 straight losses to Monarchs
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Rookie Diana Taurasi did the job on
both ends of the court Thursday night.

She had 22 points and eight rebounds to lead Phoenix to a 71-69
victory over Sacramento, ending the Mercury's eight-game losing
streak against the Monarchs.

Always praised for her offensive prowess while helping UConn to
three NCAA championships, Taurasi made the biggest defensive play
of the game against Sacramento in the final minute.

With the Mercury clinging to a three-point lead, she blocked
what appeared to be a certain basket by Monarchs center Yolanda
Griffith, then tracked down the ball near the Phoenix bench, diving
on the floor and tipping it to a teammate.

"I just got a little tip of it (the shot)," Taurasi said. "I
was surprised after I dove for it they didn't call it out of
bounds. It was close. What the heck, one more bruise doesn't mean
anything."

Phoenix had not beaten Sacramento since June 2002, and had not
won at Arco Arena since 1998.

With the Monarchs trailing 70-69, Kara Lawson went the length of
the court but missed a driving layup with two seconds left. The
Mercury's Plenette Pierson made a free throw with 1.3 seconds left
to help Phoenix win for the second night in a row.

"We don't have enough scoring to allow us to take the night off
defensively," Monarchs coach John Whisenant said. "We did things
in stretches, but we didn't play 40 minutes."

A key for Phoenix was offsetting Sacramento's strong inside
game. Both teams had 29 rebounds.

"For us to compete on the glass against a team like Sacramento
was huge," Phoenix coach Carrie Graf said. "It was our perimeter
game against their interior game. We got rebounds and that allowed
us to run."

Anna DeForge added 17 points, Pierson 13 and Penny Taylor 11 to
go with six assists.

"Our style of play is to look up, push it and run," DeForge
said. "That just gets us going. That's how we win."

Ticha Penicheiro made three 3-pointers and scored a season-high
15 points for the Monarchs, whose two-game winning streak was
snapped. Griffith added 14 points, and DeMya Walker had nine points
and seven rebounds.

Taurasi made four of six 3-point shots and added four assists
for the Mercury. Phoenix had lost twice this season to Sacramento.

Behind the perimeter shooting of Taurasi and DeForge, the
Mercury started the second half by making 10 of 15 shots for a
60-51 lead. Rebekkah Brunson scored eight points for the Monarchs,
who closed the first half with a 13-4 spurt to take a 37-35 lead.

Taurasi made three 3-pointers and scored 13 points first-half
points for Phoenix.
